Let&#39;s start by simplifying your test class:

```
class Example:
    def __init__(self):
        self.what = list(&#39;test&#39;)

    def __str__(self):
        return f&#39;This is a {self.what!s}&#39;
```

Your goal is to make an instance print `This is a test`, not `This is a [&#39;t&#39;, &#39;e&#39;, &#39;s&#39;, &#39;t&#39;]`, and for `print(Example().what)` to behave similarly by extension.

This is not as trivial as it may sound, because `what` can be any type at all. The user can set it to whatever they want in the current class, so if you don&#39;t constrain the type, you have no control over what `str(Example().what)` returns.

Another level of complication comes from the fact that python magic methods are optimized to only look at the class implementation. For example:

    class Test:
        x = 1
        def __str__(self):
            return str(x)

    t = Test()
    t.__str__ = lambda: return &#39;2&#39;

In this case, `print(str(t))` will print `1`, not `2`. This is because instance attributes are ignored in magic method lookup. Internally, `str(t)` does (approximately) `type(t).__str__(t)`, not `t.__str__()`.

Given all this background, I would propose a couple of possible solutions:

1. Use a `property` to control the type of the internal object. You can wrap in a type that has the necessary `__str__` attribute,  but also gives access to the original object:

        class Wrapper:
            def __init__(self, target):
                self.obj = target
            def __str__(self):
                return &#39;&#39;.join(self.obj)

        class Example:
            def __init__(self):
                 self.what = list(&#39;test&#39;)

            def __str__(self):
                 return f&#39;This is a {self.what!s}&#39;

            @property
            def what(self):
                return self.__dict__[&#39;what&#39;]

            @what.setter
            def what(self, value):
                self.__dict__[&#39;what&#39;] = Wrapper(value)

2. Extend option #1 to use a proper proxy object that only overrides `__str__`. This will allow you to interact directly with `Example().what` instead of `Example().what.obj`.

        class Proxy:
            def __init__(self, target):
                self.obj = target

            def __str__(self):
                return &#39;&#39;.join(self.obj)

        class Example:
            ...
            @what.setter
            def what(self, value):
                self.__dict__[&#39;what&#39;] = Proxy(value)

    The only issue is that if you re-implement `__str__` on the proxy but not other dunder methods (such as `__len__` or `__getitem__`), your proxy basically won&#39;t work. Remember that the dunder attributes can&#39;t be proxied directly, since they aren&#39;t looked up with `__getattribute__` like normal attributes when their magic function is invoked.

    You can either manually implement all known dunder attributes, or use a metaclass to generate them for you. What you can&#39;t do, unfortunately, is implement `__getattribute__` on the metaclass to trap lookups into your class, because the lookups don&#39;t happen that way for dunders.

    Here is a small example of a proxy with some generated methods. You can select the methods you want to generate:

        class ProxyMeta(type):
            dunders = (&#39;add&#39;, &#39;radd&#39;, &#39;iadd&#39;, &#39;len&#39;, &#39;iter&#39;, &#39;getitem&#39;, &#39;setitem&#39;)
            target_attr = &#39;obj&#39;

            def __init__(cls, name, bases, dct):
                def get_dunder(name):
                    def dunder(self, *args, **kwargs):
                        return getattr(getattr(self, cls.target_attr), name)(*args, **kwargs)
                    dunder.__name__ = name
                    return dunder

                for name in cls.dunders:
                    name = f&#39;__{name}__&#39;
                    setattr(cls, name, get_dunder(name))

        class Proxy(metaclass=ProxyMeta):
            def __init__(self, target):
                self.obj = target

            def __str__(self):
                return &#39;&#39;.join(self.obj)

    The only thing this updated proxy won&#39;t do (if set up correctly), is report that it is an instance of the target type when you call `isinstance` on it.

